	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Manaburn Manifesto</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Gnomish Greetings!<br />
<br />
I know some of you have given up on a fix for this AA, others do not see the importance of it in the first place.  You call those of us who have exception to the lack of a fix, idiots and the like.  Rather than return the comment in kind, I would like to explain why some of us do place value in the potential for what the AA should be, or at least my own thoughts on the subject.<br />
<br />
When I see some of the suggestions for fixes on the AA, I can't help but think that these people can't possibly have experienced the original Manaburn, or at least do not grasp how effective many of the Luclin fast damage AAs are for other classes.  Many of these AAs were even upgraded in future expansions, while Manaburn becomes less and less effective just because of the way it is capped and therefore scales.  Game mechanics have changed, removing the downside of AAs that depended on line of sight which affected True Shot, as well as bolt type of spells.  Auto fire for ranged attack means that Rangers no longer have to actively press fire to make the most of the ability.  Lifeburn had no longer drained all but a sliver of the Necro's hitpoints, etc.<br />
<br />
Why do I bother to bring these things up, they were obviously broken.  Well, so was Manaburn.  Only Manaburn wasn't broken at release, it was broken by a nerf that occurred close to the end of the expansion it was introduced in.  We were told in advance that it was going to be nerfed, although many of us question the validity of the reason for it as well as the implementation of the fix.<br />
<br />
What happened to bring about this change?  Well, we were told that a new expansion was being released and they wanted to change the way the raiding game was designed.  Instead of creating encounters that simply had huge hitpoints they were going to make quick damage play a larger factor.  We also saw after release that scripting groups of encounters played a large role in design.  The didn't want the ability to make most encounters trivial by Manaburn where wizards Trod'ed up to full mana then make the boss mob vaporize.  They knew that mana caps would increase dramatically as a result of higher levels and new equipment in PoP.<br />
<br />
What we the wizard community were told was that they did not have a problem with old content becoming trivial because of Luclin AAs.  In the beginning when asked, developers and SOE correspondents communicated that they did not see a problem with Manaburn as it existed.  This however was not the feeling of some other classes, or at least some members of other classes.  There arose in the EQ community an out cry over groups of wizards who would group together and vaporize Kunark era dragons and bosses.  Because they could port, they could deploy quickly and get a jump on other groups who might want to tackle the encounter.<br />
<br />
Within the wizard community feeling over Manaburn squads were split.  Many of the high end players didn't see the cause for an uproar and rightfully pointed out that these encounters were being one grouped already by multitudes of classes.  There was even an occasional brag of a solo or boxed kill by other classes.  Lower tier players saw great potential to help their guilds with Manaburn to get their members their epics.  A few did not like to have to bargain or contend with Manaburn squads to get these players Epic 1.0.  I won't go into the ethics of what occurred, as at least some of these MB squads had good intentions and shared freely with lesser tier players the epic drops.  But, you can see where the nerf was not a total surprise.  It was even foreshadowed by the Great Manaburn Nerf Hoax on these boards.<br />
<br />
SOE comes to Graffe's and says Manaburn is going to change, regardless of the prior statements during conferences to the contrary.  The reason given was not it's current potential in Luclin, nor the MB Squads monopolizing Kunark content, but a new expansion packed with low hp, high damage mob encounters that would not work with infinitely stackable Manaburn.  The wizard community wanted that type of expansion and path, because we were so dependant on mana to contribute.  There was outrage, but there was also support for the nerf partly due to the promise of the expansion but also from sympathy for the Kunark epic people.<br />
<br />
The adjustment to Manaburn was to be a reburn timer preventing simultaneous burns.  That is the extent of what was communicated to us on the boards.  That meant to most, the end of Manaburn squads, or at least the ease of doing it.  That was huge, and it took away the biggest utility of the ability to dispatch raid mobs when things went south.  SOE decided that we would have to wait a full minute, 10 ticks between burns.  I find that time outrageous.  There was hope before the implementation what was on test that they would see this and reduce it to a more reasonable number.  It effectually limited any encounter to a single wizard Manaburning, a limit not imposed on the classes' special abilities.<br />
<br />
But, you see that was not the full extent of the nerf.  SOE lied to us by omission.  No one communicated that AA criticals would no longer affect Manaburn.  There was still hope that the single wizard might still contribute meaningfully after depleting all of his mana by a lucky critical that would kill the mob and save the day.  It is unclear whether this was intentional or a result of placing a debuff on the mob making the code treat it like a damage over time and not an instant spell.  To this day, no one from SOE has said which is the case.  It could still critical with the natural 1 - 2% ability to crit, but it occured much less frequently and that may, in itself, have taken special code.  Again, we don't know because it wasn't communicated at the time.<br />
<br />
Yet, that still was not the full extent of the nerf.  One more deficit showed its face; they placed a hard cap on the total damage.  Not on the base damage, which some may have been able to understand, but on the total damage possible even with a critical.  But, guess what.  They . . . did  . . . not  . . . cap  . . . the  . . . mana   . . . used.  They didn't even cap the damage at what was possible at the end of Luclin, they capped it at less than half of what it could do prior to the nerf, 9492.  (and where in hell did that number come from?)  Gone were the days of 5 digit damage numbers, at least until recently.  What happened to &quot;We are comfortable with Manaburn, and old content is going to be trivial, no problem&quot;? - no communication.<br />
<br />
I and others fully expected that PoP boss mobs would, by and large, be low hitpoint bosses.  Wizards on release of Velious and Luclin, found the 100k+ bosses to be unfriendly to a highly mana dependant class.  Velious had much lower regen caps and higher mob resists, and healers felt it along with us.  Luclin brought the 'god rod' to overcome mana problems but still had encounters that played like a marathon rather than a game.  Well, the resist system was revamped to make it more friendly to all damage casters and Trods (god rods) had a reuse timer added as a whole separate nerf (but needed).  However, PoP mobs still had significant hps and all of the significant ones had scripted encounter to get to the boss or multiple bosses.  This meant you didn't wait after getting to a certain point to set up an encounter to regain mana for the most part.  Conventional spells got bigger and better to compensate, so as an expansion it was balanced.  There was only a handful of lesser encounters were Luclin damage potential Manaburn would make any difference.  The reason for the nerf seemed a farce, a lie, an exaggeration at best.  No Manaburn team was going to be going from encounter to encounter blowing away the bosses.<br />
<br />
It was obvious to us that the nerf went way overboard and that Manaburn was not only worthless, but getting worse with each incremental expansion.  Other classes Luclin abilities' were being improved, expanded, or repaired.  But, not Manaburn.<br />
<br />
Over a year ago, we were asked what was not balanced for the wizard class.  While Manaburn was not everybody's number once choice for a first fix, it was overwhelmingly the most popular choice of the community.  Even those who did not find it a big problem could agree that, if anyone thing in our class could be labeled as broken, Manaburn would be it.  <br />
<br />
I really expected that to be the turning point.  We would at last see this long broken ability regain what should not have been taken in the first place.  We got some hearsay confirmation that the developers understood that it was broken.  I was told by multiple people that a fix was imminent, we would not be waiting long.  It was a priority.  Natan, told me otherwise.  I didn't want to believe his words, but it is looking like he has more foresight than many of you want to give him credit for.  The longer this sits idle the more disillusioned I become.  Not only with Manaburn, but with SOE in general.  Yes, I am still mad.  The impending fix?  Seems like a lie to me, certainly not a priority given the bulk of changes that have happened in the last year.  <br />
<br />
It is possible they want to give us a token fix. Not really anything even resembling what Manaburn was meant to be.  I am sorry, that is not acceptable in my opinion.  This is a debt way past due, and is gaining interest with each passing month.  Some of you want to accept or propose lesser Manaburns, that does not cut it with some of us.  I think SOE wants to jump on these and give us next to nothing to placate those of us bugging them for a fix.  It should have at least as much value as the original Manaburn, anything less is a cop out.<br />
<br />
<b>This is my expectation and my post on the SOE board:</b><br />
1)  Allow it to crit to where it did pre-nerf.  There were reports of a few in excess of 20k crits before it was adjusted at the end of Luclin. <br />
<br />
2)  If you absolutely must, cap the base and allow both natural and AA crits to affect it like it used to. (Cap 10 - 10.4, allow to crit) <br />
<br />
3)  Remove the reburn timer.  How can it be justified to not allow Wizard fast damage to stack when most, if not all, other classes fast damage abilities stack?  I think the majority of the playerbase agree that wizards are supposed to be the fast damage experts, to have ours not stack while other classes' do is the opposite of what one would expect.  It is not fair to penalize the wizard class as a whole for the indiscretion of a few who may have, in the past, monopolized content. <br />
<br />
4)  Don't drain mana, use mana like a spell.  10.4k base damage (20.8k critical) would have used 4160 mana at best efficiency of 2.5 dmg/mana.  We didn't have mana by numbers, but wizards had a pretty good idea of their mana pool and estimated the best efficiency at 2.4 to 2.5 damage per mana.<br />
<br />
We talk about how we are losing ground in quick damage margin over other classes.  We talk about how our utility is weak, the kind of damage Manaburn did can be used strategically granting some of that.  It is time for them to put their money where their mouth is, fix Manaburn already.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
