<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
			
			<div id="postmenu_580535">
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=0b46511ea3223c490c85478a876cc3df&amp;u=247">Gwideon</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_580535", true); </script>
			</div>
                        
<div class="smallfont"><img src="images/supporter.gif" alt="" border="0" /></div>

			<div class="smallfont">Manaburn or bust!</div>
			
			
			<!-- Avatars -->		
			
			<!-- /Avatars -->
			<div class="smallfont">
<br>



<br />

</div>
				
				<div>
					
					
				</div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Gnomish Greetings!<br />
<br />
Thank ye kindly fer the validation Maevenniia, I think they have to address it sometime before EQ closes its doors.  Whether you and I are around to see it is another question altogether.  Maybe after the last of the olde crew has moved on to other persuits, a token fix as I mentioned will be accepted by those who don't know the history.  I do however think that something will eventually be done.  So far your and Natan's expectations for Manaburn have been truer than mine.<br />
<br />
Annoid, I do not think SOE hates any class.  I think they believed we are balanced or perhaps even overpowered.  Where did they get that impression?  I think Graffe's posters gave it to them.  Wizards like to brag.  We threorize unobtainable max damage capabilites and post them as if they were happening.  We had a senior group of wizards who were continually at the end game and were able to realize the full potential of the class with all of the toys, spells, and support crew.  <br />
<br />
What they failed to recognize or chose not to acknowledge was how dependant on other classes we were in those situations.  Instead of allocating the amount of damage we were doing to those who provided the support and made it possible we claimed it all ours. They were, after all, spells we cast so the damage must be ours.  We would fail to recognize those who disagreed with these assumptions, ignoring group play to emphasize raid value.<br />
<br />
What should have happened is we slice up the damage we do and give credit to the class that helped.  If they were not there, the damage would not be.  Slice off a percentage and give it to the Druid for 9/Steel and Ro.  Slice off a percentage and give it to the Enchanter for VoQ/Clairv over KEI.  Slice off a percentage to the Bard who played focus and mana regen.  Slice off a percentage to the Magician for Trod and debuff, to the Beastlord for SD and Paragon, to the Cleric for BoR, to the Tank for the hate cap margin they provide.<br />
<br />
Some argued that some of these were just buffs and that you could get them in PoK.  They were available in MGB to an entire raid, or by 'boxed alts'.  I still think credit is due to these classes.  Lately we can not count on having this entire group especially with declining attendance. Beastlords and Magicians have been missed lately by myself, and after an untimely death I was looking for a druid for a 9, and had to do without.<br />
<br />
We brag, and other classes believed it.  You should have seen the misinformation I encountered on the Paladin board just before they improved pure melee.  I spent considerable time correcting the information, but other boards did not seem to have the 'voices of reason' that were prevelant here on Graffe's.  We would run some of these folks out of town on a rail for the 'whines' they portrayed, had they posted here.  So, this disinformation spread unabated.<br />
<br />
I have heard valid arguments here that we should not allow the Graffe board to digress into a class rant fest.  In a way I think we are seeing the result of this.  No rants = class balanced or overpowered?  Who knows where devs came up with how to allocate upgrades and nerfs.  It appears that they did not do it off of damage logs, perhaps theoritical or even observation of a few encounters.  As much as Beta testing has improved, I do not give it much weight.  I signed up for Beta and could not get Gwideon transfered to the OoW beta server.  I created a 65 Wizard who was far better equipped than Gwideon.  He had ancients, GoD and Time raid gear, and decent AAs.  <br />
<br />
Do I think they tested for my level of play?  No.  I think they have in the past and continue to balance the highest level of play, anticipating that we will all get there to some point.  I wonder if it came as a surprise that lower tier guilds were having as much trouble as they were in PoP with flagging.  I don't think they weigh what can be gotten easily for each class in regards to equipment, spells and AA.  In otherwords a 'base' abilites example of the class.<br />
<br />
I could be wrong overall, but I see at least examples of where errors have been made in this area.  I think the game has become so huge, they would be overwhelmed to manage this many classes and expansions at all levels.  I also believe they rely in part on information read from these boards to find errors in balance.  If you as a board, have the 'voice of reason', that could work to your disadvantage.  Suppose a class is entirely wrong on their list orf rants, and in spite of the cries of the whiners they are really pretty well off?  Is SOE going to step in and tell them they are wrong, ignore the comments, depend on those 'voices of reason'?  Bad things happen which ever approach they take, they have learned it to be a lose/lose situation.  Whether some of these classes chose to acknowledge it or not, some very nice things have happened for them.<br />
<br />
I think they should rent out Claud by the hour to pummel these other boards into submission.  <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" />  Right or wrong he is a good debater when he does not digress.  They might have had class representatives in mind for the job, who knows.  <br />
<br />
Sorry, there must be Entish blood somewhere in my family tree as I do not seem to be able to say anything simply and to the point.  Be at least content that you are not subjected to the subject of pencils.  In my prior guild, one of the officers did not believe my propensity to expand on a topic and taunted me to write on the subject.  Before I was even halfway through my essay I had something like 1800 words and hadn't even touched on the finer points of pencils (pun intended).</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
		<!-- edit note -->
			<div class="smallfont">			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
				<em>
				Last edited by Gwideon : December 29th, 2004 at <span class="time">10:00 PM</span>.
				
				</em>
