		<!-- message -->
		<div>Gnomish Greetings!<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Ambrielle</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">First, well said Gwideon <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Actually once spawned this is probably the fight that would be most affected by restoring manaburn, as MB has very low hp but with its AEs can kill your raid extremely fast, so dps is crucial.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
Thank ye kindly!<br />
<br />
After the nerf of Manaburn, there were a few wizards who avidly defended the castration of the ability.  The most common examples given were Manaetic Behemoth and the Croc in Plane of Earth.  Qaman in the Manaburn thread on SOE's boards, cites Coirnav in Plane of Water as well.  <br />
<br />
First, those that defend the nerf gave no consideration to what was necessary to get to the script point where you could even use the ability.  Our guild struggled more with spider control than with MB himself.  His AE was brutal, but if you had enough coordinated healing power for the main tank, you extended the fight where quick damage was less of a dependancy.  Once you reached that point, conventional nukes would start to overtake Manaburn.  Only if your healers risked running out of mana to heal the main tank or spider CC was not solid would Manaburn edge ahead of conventional nukes.<br />
<br />
The Manaetic Behemoth is a progression mob, but in the grand scheme of the entire PoP progression chart he is a mere sliver of what is needed.  So what if it failed to slow progression for the upper tier guilds as long as it did.  By the time Gates was released it was trivial to so many guilds, that Manaburn would not have made any significant difference.  He still had something like 150k hitpoints. So, where they worried that for one encounter a guild might get 10 - 15 Manaburn wizards to avoid using a main tank and healers?  It has been brought up before:  If you have that many wizards available with full mana by the time he is targetable, it is likely going to be trivial anyway.  Why would they feel it necessary to force you to use a tank healer tactic for every single boss encounter?  Shouldn't it be okay to occasionally think outside of the box, and do things in unconventional means?  Its not like that would work for anything close to a significant number of encounters.<br />
<br />
The Croc in PoE holds the key to the caves that lead to the Arbiter of Earth, another minor obstacle.  One needed per guild, or even a friend that has one.  You would still need to clear a fight area, and I don't think you can avoid the adds of the encounter.  Coirnav in POW?  I find it laughable to think that, while the encounter is still a challenge to the guild, a wizard would have enough mana available to him to use Manaburn effectively.<br />
<br />
If a handful of events became slightly easier, so what?  Why couldn't  Manaburn be a legitimate tactic that a guild used?  Risk an all or nothing win/loss by blowing your wizard's mana on a single strike.  Who really believes that these events are cast in stone?  Couldn't there have been a hitpoint adjustment to the mob to allow for a certain number of Manaburns; give the boss an extra 30k hps.   <br />
<br />
If the EQ community really still believes that this nerf is necessary, then perhaps this unstackable penalty needs to be put in perspective for their abilities.  How they feel if only one Ranger could use True Shot for the length of the discipline, or if Harm Touch bounced, or Life Burn, Heart of Flame, or any other AAs that are used to compress damage or that are regularly used in a raid encounter.  In general the game has a whole, has gone the other direction.  Dots of the same type did not used to stack, debuff slots on the mobs were highly limited.  Yet, these things were done to allow other classes' damage stack better.  Did the wizard community jeer?  No, just as I would fully expect the EQ community to support a fix for Manaburn.<br />
<br />
If some misinformed member of another class decides that Manaburn still needs to be nerfed as it is currently, I say we tar and feather them.  It is a double standard, and they should not condone it just because it doesn't affect them.  I saw one poster on this board go back to his community board, and have the gall to criticize that SOE was looking at fixes for Manaburn.  He was also a class that saw a lot of improvements to game play that directly affect him in the last year.  Why?  I can only believe it is due to people not understanding the situation, or class envy.  The first is fixable; the second, intolerable.<br />
<br />
Lady Tiesiaan, I am not sure it would stand as posted there, as I have made some comments that I am sure they would not appreciate.  I didn't like that my comment from the port thread was edited, and I thought the comment polite.  SOE does read these boards.  I like Graffe's much better.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
